The author expresses disappointment in the Supreme Court's ruling in New York State Rifle & Pistol Association v. Bruen. They argue that the ruling contradicts common sense and the Constitution, as it strikes down New York's authority to protect its citizens by requiring a need to carry a concealed weapon in public. The author emphasizes the need to do more to protect Americans from gun violence, especially in light of recent attacks. They highlight their commitment to reducing gun violence and urge states to enact and enforce sensible gun laws. The author also mentions that the Second Amendment is not absolute and that states have historically regulated gun ownership. They call on Americans to speak out on gun safety, as lives are at stake.